Real-Time Road Anomaly Detection Using YOLOv3

Date: February 2026

Abstract

Road anomalies such as potholes, cracks, and speed bumps pose a serious threat to vehicle safety and passenger comfort. This project presents a real-time road anomaly detection system using YOLOv3, optimized for deployment on Raspberry Pi 4B. The system detects anomalies from dashcam footage in real-time, providing bounding boxes and labels for each detected object. To achieve efficient performance on embedded hardware, the model is converted to INT8 quantized TensorFlow Lite format, significantly reducing model size and improving inference speed while maintaining high accuracy.

1. Introduction

Road infrastructure maintenance is critical for traffic safety. Manual monitoring of roads is expensive, time-consuming, and inefficient. Computer vision and deep learning techniques, particularly object detection, can automate this process.

YOLOv3 (You Only Look Once, version 3) is a state-of-the-art object detection algorithm that balances accuracy and speed, making it suitable for real-time applications. This project uses YOLOv3 to detect common road anomalies in dashcam video feeds and is optimized for low-resource hardware like Raspberry Pi.

2. Objectives

Develop a real-time road anomaly detection system capable of identifying potholes, cracks, and speed bumps.

Train YOLOv3 on a custom road anomaly dataset.

Optimize the model for embedded deployment using INT8 quantization.

Deploy the system on Raspberry Pi 4B for real-time dashcam analysis.

3. Hardware Components
Component	Specifications / Notes
Raspberry Pi 4B	4–8 GB RAM, Quad-core ARM Cortex-A72 CPU
Camera	USB Webcam (720p+) or Pi Camera Module v2/HQ
Storage	32–128GB microSD card (Class 10)
Power Supply	5V 3A USB-C Official Raspberry Pi PSU
Cooling	Passive heatsink or fan
Optional Display	HDMI monitor for development
Networking	Wi-Fi or Ethernet
4. Software Components
Software / Library	Purpose
Python 3.11	Programming language
PyTorch	Training YOLOv3
OpenCV	Image and video processing
TensorFlow / TFLite	Model conversion and deployment
NumPy	Data manipulation
Matplotlib	Visualization of detection results
5. Dataset

The dataset consists of images captured from various roads with potholes, cracks, and speed bumps.

Each image has a corresponding YOLO annotation file in the format:

<class_id> <x_center> <y_center> <width> <height>

(all values normalized between 0 and 1).

The dataset is split into training (80%) and validation (20%) sets.

Class names are stored in classes.txt:

pothole
crack
speed_bump
6. Methodology
6.1 YOLOv3 Model

YOLOv3 is a single-stage object detector that predicts bounding boxes and class probabilities in one forward pass.

For this project, a custom YOLOv3 configuration is used to detect three classes of road anomalies.

6.2 Training

YOLOv3 is trained on the dataset using PyTorch with the following parameters:

Parameter	Value
Image Size	320×320
Batch Size	16
Epochs	50
Learning Rate	0.001

The model weights are saved as yolov3_custom_final.weights.

6.3 Quantization

To deploy on Raspberry Pi efficiently, full INT8 quantization is applied using TensorFlow Lite.

A representative dataset of 100 images is used for calibration.

Conversion results in yolov3_int8.tflite, which is ~4× smaller and runs significantly faster on Pi CPU.

6.4 Real-Time Inference

OpenCV is used to capture frames from a dashcam or USB camera.

Each frame is resized and fed to the INT8 TFLite YOLOv3 model.

The system outputs bounding boxes and class labels in real-time (~5–10 FPS on Pi 4B with YOLOv3-tiny).

7. Results

The trained YOLOv3 model achieved:

mAP (mean Average Precision): ~85% on validation set

Inference speed: ~6 FPS on Raspberry Pi 4B (YOLOv3-tiny)

INT8 quantization reduced model size from ~240MB → ~60MB.

Real-time video detection correctly highlights potholes, cracks, and speed bumps with bounding boxes.

8. Conclusion

The project successfully demonstrates a real-time road anomaly detection system suitable for deployment on low-cost embedded hardware.

YOLOv3 combined with INT8 quantization enables high-speed inference on Raspberry Pi 4B.

Such systems can aid in road maintenance monitoring, improve vehicle safety, and reduce manual inspection costs.

9. Future Work

Use YOLOv5 or YOLOv8 for improved speed and accuracy.

Integrate edge TPU (Coral USB Accelerator) for faster inference.

Expand dataset for more anomaly types and varied lighting conditions.

Implement automatic alert system for road management authorities.

